91":"1491","abt 1456":"about 1456","1435":"1435","Abt 1470":"about 1470","1512":"1512","1534":"1534","1456":"1456","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1463":"1463","1485":"1485","1529":"1529","1537":"1537","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Bramford, Suffolk, England":"Bramford, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Collins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Colin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish and Manx: shortened Anglicized from <b>Ó Coileáin</b>, compare   Cullen  , or in Man or west Ulster shortened from <b>Mac Coileáin</b>, compare   McQuillan   and   McCallion  . The genitival <i>-s</i> is a local addition to   Collin   and variants after the surname was Anglicized.","Americanized form of French   Colin   or   Collin   and also   Collette  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Colin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Alfredo, Francisco, Jesus, Ricardo, Alberto, Angel, Arturo, Eduardo, Esteban, Faustino.  French Alexandre, Andre, Armand, Georges, Henri, Jean Claude, Jean-Michel, Laurette, Lucien, Marcel, Patrice, Pierre.","French, Walloon, and Breton: from a French shortened pet form of the personal name   Nicolas   (see   Nicholas  ). This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","English: from the personal name <i>Colin</i>, a diminutive of <i>Col</i>, itself a pet form of   Nicholas  ."]},{"name":"Kolenc","meanings":["Slovenian:","topographic name derived from <i>koleno</i> ‘knee’.","nickname from the dialect plant name <i>kolenc</i> ‘yellow bedstraw (Galium verum)’ or ‘common nipplewort (Lapsana communis)’. Compare   Collins   3."]},{"name":"Callins","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Collins  ."]},{"name":"Collings","meanings":["English: variant of   Collins   or   Colling  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"McKinley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhionnlaigh</b>, a patronymic from the early personal name <i>Fionnlaoch</i> (see   Finley  ).","History: William McKinley (1843–1901), 25th US president, was born at Niles, OH, a descendant of David McKinley, known as ‘David the Weaver’, of Scotch–Irish stock, who settled in York County, PA, <i>c.</i> 1743. William McKinley's family were iron founders who tracked the ore from the Susquehanna Valley in PA to Columbiana County, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"McKinlay","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scottish Alastair.","Scottish: variant of   McKinley  ."]},{"name":"Finley","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Scottish Gaelic name Fionnlagh  or a transferred use of the surname derived from the given name. This is one of a set of Celtic names which in recent years has also been favoured increasingly among parents without Scottish connections. It is also used occasionally for girls."]},{"name":"Quinley","meanings":["English: apparently an altered form of Scottish   McKinley   or a shortened form of Irish <b>McQuinnelly</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Coingheallaigh</b> or <b>Ó Coingheallaigh</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Coingheallach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘faithful to pledges’. This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":20,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John McKinley Collins was born in 1435, in Bramford, Suffolk, England, his father, Thomas Collins, was 25 and his mother, Manerva Amos, was 15. He married Cynthia Narcisus Vassey about 1456, in Bramford, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1534, in his hometown, at the age of 99."},"et":{"1435–1534":"1435–1534","1440–1491":"1440–1491","1460–1560":"1460–1560","1462–1529":"1462–1529","1463–1512":"1463–1512","1477–Male":"1477–Surnud","1485–1537":"1485–1537","1410–1456":"1410–1456","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1462":"1462","1440":"1440","1560":"1560","1460":"1460","June 1491":"juuni 1491","1470":"1470","1491":"1491","abt 1456":"umbes 1456","1435":"1435","Abt 1470":"umbes 1470","1512":"1512","1534":"1534","1456":"1456","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1463":"1463","1485":"1485","1529":"1529","1537":"1537","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bramford, Suffolk, England":"Bramford, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1435–1534":"1435–1534","1440–1491":"1440–1491","1460–1560":"1460–1560","1462–1529":"1462–1529","1463–1512":"1463–1512","1477–Male":"1477–Kuollut","1485–1537":"1485–1537","1410–1456":"1410–1456","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1462":"1462","1440":"1440","1560":"1560","1460":"1460","June 1491":"kesäkuu 1491","1470":"1470","1491":"1491","abt 1456":"noin 1456","1435":"1435","Abt 1470":"noin 1470","1512":"1512","1534":"1534","1456":"1456","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1463":"1463","1485":"1485","1529":"1529","1537":"1537","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bramford, Suffolk, England":"Bramford, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1435–1534":"1435–1534","1440–1491":"1440–1491","1460–1560":"1460–1560","146